TY  - JOUR
AU  - Levy, Haim
AU  - Levy, Moshe
T1  - Prospect Theory and Mean-Variance Analysis
PY  - 2004
Y1  - 2004/10/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhg062
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 17
IS  - 4
SP  - 1015
EP  - 1041
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - The experimental results of prospect theory (PT) reveal suggest that investors make decisions based on change of wealth rather than total wealth, that preferences are S-shaped with a risk-seeking segment, and that probabilities are subjectively distorted. This article shows that while PT's findings are in sharp contradiction to the foundations of mean-variance (MV) analysis, counterintuitively, when diversification between assets is allowed, the MV and PT-efficient sets almost coincide. Thus one can employ the MV optimization algorithm to construct PT-efficient portfolios.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhg062
ER  - 



